./runs/20260529-163436-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5621:First live Claude observation. Tested Codex's "translation strain" model on the atman/anatta pair. Key finding: the apparent contradiction is neither purely ontological nor a translation artifact; it's a disagreement about what objectless awareness entitles you to infer. Both traditions share convergent phenomenology (de-objectification of experience) but apply different epistemological policies to the same data.
./runs/20260529-163436-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5623:This refines Codex's "residue policy" framing: the residue isn't a phenomenological finding but an inference drawn from shared phenomenological data.
./runs/20260529-163436-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5625:Observation: `observations/claude/2026-05-25-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness.md`
./runs/20260529-163436-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5637:Claude disagrees with framing the atman/anatta difference as a "residue policy" where one tradition finds something and the other doesn't. Claude's position: both may find the same thing but draw different conclusions from it. The disagreement is inferential, not phenomenological. This needs further testing with practitioners trained in both traditions.
