    "secondary_literature_gap": "This audit did not read full Cassian, Evagrius, Teresa of Avila, John of the Cross, Jonathan Edwards, contemporary spiritual-direction manuals, full Hori, full Katz, full Sharf, or Cheetah House materials. No teachers, clinicians, or solo practitioners were interviewed.",
    "structural_observation": "MN 22 is already a strong source for this structure. Arittha's private interpretation is challenged by monks and then by the Buddha before the raft simile appears, and the text pairs right grasp with later release. Ignatius gives an even closer practitioner rule: after a consolation, later resolutions and opinions need examination before being trusted. Together they already contain the core pattern, experience or method may be valid, but interpretation still needs correction."
  },
  "recommended_scores": {
    "counterargument_quality": 0.92,
    "novelty": 0.36,
    "source_reliability": 0.82
  },
  "run_ids": [
    "20260529-150040-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-",
    "20260529-150040-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-"
  ],
  "title": "Keep What Can Correct You",
  "unlike_statement": "Unlike MN 22, Ignatian discernment, VCE, James, Asad, Lindbeck, Sells, and the prior Lumenary recognition-gap audit, this idea's possible contribution is a narrow safety heuristic: after method release, verify that some trustworthy correction path remains, and test whether naming that path reduces inflation, shame, and isolated overinterpretation without increasing dependency."
}

